[{"id": 3406893, "title": "Pantallas para ver el mundo. Estereotipaci\u00f3n televisiva de la poblaci\u00f3n ind\u00edgena mexicana y generaci\u00f3n de prejuicio // Screens to See the World. Television Stereotypes of the Mexican Indigenous Population and the Generation of Prejudice", "created_at": "2013-04-27T20:46:14.215-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/3406893/Pantallas_para_ver_el_mundo_Estereotipaci%C3%B3n_televisiva_de_la_poblaci%C3%B3n_ind%C3%ADgena_mexicana_y_generaci%C3%B3n_de_prejuicio_Screens_to_See_the_World_Television_Stereotypes_of_the_Mexican_Indigenous_Population_and_the_Generation_of_Prejudice?f_ri=72282", "dom_id": "work_3406893", "summary": "Resumen:\r\nIntroducci\u00f3n. Los estereotipos son creencias estructuradas socialmente sobre un grupo social concreto, que pueden derivar del contacto directo o indirecto con miembros de ese grupo. En este sentido, se ha planteado que los medios de comunicaci\u00f3n pueden generar un proceso de estereotipaci\u00f3n que conlleva la activaci\u00f3n de estereotipos que impactan en actitudes m\u00e1s o menos prejuiciosas. Objetivos. El estudio busca estudiar si este proceso se produce con respecto a la poblaci\u00f3n ind\u00edgena mexicana, en el contexto de la Zona Metropolitana de Monterrey.Metodolog\u00eda. Se realiz\u00f3 un estudio en dos fases: en la primera se analiz\u00f3 mediante un an\u00e1lisis de contenido los estereotipos medi\u00e1ticos de los ind\u00edgenas en los programas de ficci\u00f3n de la televisi\u00f3n; en la segunda se evalu\u00f3 mediante una encuesta la relaci\u00f3n entre las creencias y la actitud prejuiciosa demostrada hacia la poblaci\u00f3n ind\u00edgena por los estudiantes de bachillerato de la zona metropolitana de Monterrey. Conclusiones. Los resultados reflejan el impacto del consumo y de los estereotipos sobre el nivel de prejuicio mantenido, pero no as\u00ed un proceso de estereotipaci\u00f3n.\r\n \r\nAbstract:\r\nIntroduction. Stereotypes are socially-structured beliefs about a particular social group, which can be derived from direct or indirect contact with members of that group. In this regard, it has been pointed out that media representations can generate and reinforce stereotypes that lead to the development of more or less prejudiced attitudes. Objectives. This study seeks to examine whether this process occurs with respect to the Mexican indigenous population, in the context of the metropolitan area of Monterrey. Methods. The study combined two methods: the first one consisted of the content analysis of fiction TV programmes in order to identify possible stereotypes about Mexico\u2019s indigenous population; the second instrument was a survey applied to high school students of the metropolitan area of Monterrey in order to investigate the relationship between their beliefs and prejudiced attitudes towards indigenous people. Conclusions. Results confirmed the impact of the consumption of media stereotypes on the level of prejudice towards indigenous people, but not on the stereotyping of this sector of the population.\r\n ", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 31189534, "asset_id": 3406893, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 1823375, "first_name": "Plataforma", "last_name": "Revistas Comunicaci\u00f3n", "domain_name": "independent", "page_name": "PlataformaLatinaRevistasComunicaci\u00f3n", "display_name": "Plataforma Revistas Comunicaci\u00f3n", "profile_url": "https://independent.academia.edu/PlataformaLatinaRevistasComunicaci%C3%B3n?f_ri=72282", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/1823375/621515/14878854/s65_plataforma_latina.revistas_comunicaci_n.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 926, "name": "Indigenous Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Indigenous_Studies?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 5906, "name": "Prejudice", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Prejudice?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 72282, "name": "Television Consumption", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television_Consumption?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 100383, "name": "Stereotyping", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Stereotyping?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 277484, "name": "Estereotipos", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Estereotipos?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 350571, "name": "Ind\u00edgenas", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Ind%C3%ADgenas?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 795191, "name": "Rejuicio", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Rejuicio?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 795192, "name": "Consumo Televisivo", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Consumo_Televisivo?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 795194, "name": "Media Stereotypes", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Media_Stereotypes?f_ri=72282"}]}, {"id": 76715722, "title": "Transformations of television consumption practices: An analysis on documentary viewing among post-millennials", "created_at": "2022-04-17T08:23:50.235-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/76715722/Transformations_of_television_consumption_practices_An_analysis_on_documentary_viewing_among_post_millennials?f_ri=72282", "dom_id": "work_76715722", "summary": "The adaptation of new infrastructure in the media industry, as well as the evolution of Web 2.0 and beyond, has decisively altered the ways of producing and consuming audiovisual content. The forthcoming generation of viewers are the post-millennials who have been born and raised within a digital world with completely different consumption patterns when compared to the previous generations. This comparative study aims to explore and assess the transformations of audiovisual consumption practices within the current digital environment. Specifically, the research focuses on examining audiovisual consumption patterns on documentary viewing utilizing focus group method; Greece and Cyprus were selected as case study locations, due to their interconnected culture and origins. The results are presented in a dual level; initially the ways post-millennials of Greece and Cyprus consume web & traditional documentaries are examined. Moreover, the patterns of audiovisual content consumption, com...", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 84328919, "asset_id": 76715722, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 18178415, "first_name": "Maria", "last_name": "Matsiola", "domain_name": "uowm", "page_name": "MariaMatsiola", "display_name": "Maria Matsiola", "profile_url": "https://uowm.academia.edu/MariaMatsiola?f_ri=72282", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/18178415/5077572/23226100/s65_maria.matsiola.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 1571, "name": "Television Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television_Studies?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 12006, "name": "Interactive Media", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Interactive_Media?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 54718, "name": "Media Consumption", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Media_Consumption?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 63004, "name": "Interactive Documentary", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Interactive_Documentary?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 72282, "name": "Television Consumption", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television_Consumption?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 146107, "name": "Television Viewing", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television_Viewing?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 234693, "name": "Generation Z", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Generation_Z?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 400945, "name": "Participations", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Participations?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 631871, "name": "Web Documentary", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Web_Documentary?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 1115281, "name": "Young News Audience", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Young_News_Audience?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 1747972, "name": "Z Generation", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Z_Generation?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 1870310, "name": "Millennials attitudes", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Millennials_attitudes?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 2974297, "name": "Television-viewing habits", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television-viewing_habits?f_ri=72282"}]}, {"id": 1820255, "title": "Imagining Transnational Modernity in Contemporary Malaysia: Malay Women, Asian Soap Operas, and Moral Capabilities", "created_at": "2012-07-29T16:50:02.605-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/1820255/Imagining_Transnational_Modernity_in_Contemporary_Malaysia_Malay_Women_Asian_Soap_Operas_and_Moral_Capabilities?f_ri=72282", "dom_id": "work_1820255", "summary": "\"This paper is concerned with how urban Malay women negotiate and imagine their modernity as mediated through imported television dramas. It is clear that one of the platforms through which to articulate modernity in contemporary Malaysia is the consumption of popular culture. Promoted at first as an appropriate television genre to strengthen the agenda of Malaysian modernity, Asian soap opera has not been without its tensions. Some authorities have expressed anxiety over what they consider to be the negative influences of foreign issues of morality, which they believe might undermine the standards of Malay woman- hood and compromise Malay cultural and national boundaries. Against this perception, however, we propose that urban Malay women negotiate their cultural re- sources to establish specific watching competencies with which to intelligently and adeptly engage foreign lifestyles in Asian soap operas imported to Malaysia. Watching competencies involve an active mobilization of those resources through which Malay women watch these soaps and measure their adherence to tradition. This paper will focus on how selected urban Malay women exercise their cultural resources, particularly those of adat (the traditional Malay custom as practiced by the Malays in Malaysia) and Islam, to form specific watching competencies for engaging with the depictions of complex inappropriate foreign lifestyles portrayed in Asian soap operas.\r\n\"", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 25340557, "asset_id": 1820255, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 261622, "first_name": "MD", "last_name": "Azalanshah", "domain_name": "malaya", "page_name": "MDAzalanshah", "display_name": "MD Azalanshah", "profile_url": "https://malaya.academia.edu/MDAzalanshah?f_ri=72282", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/261622/64412/71034/s65_md.azalanshah.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 188, "name": "Cultural Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Cultural_Studies?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 696, "name": "Gender Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Gender_Studies?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 859, "name": "Communication", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Communication?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 928, "name": "Media Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Media_Studies?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 934, "name": "Media and Cultural Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Media_and_Cultural_Studies?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 997, "name": "Reception Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Reception_Studies?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 1138, "name": "Women's Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Womens_Studies?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 1571, "name": "Television Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television_Studies?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 2858, "name": "Popular Culture", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Popular_Culture?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 3143, "name": "Audience Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Audience_Studies?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 4195, "name": "Cultural Theory", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Cultural_Theory?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 5583, "name": "Audience and Reception Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Audience_and_Reception_Studies?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 7024, "name": "Gender", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Gender?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 9538, "name": "Consumer Behavior", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Consumer_Behavior?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 10758, "name": "Modernity", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Modernity?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 11483, "name": "Cultural Memory", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Cultural_Memory?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 13666, "name": "Consumer Culture", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Consumer_Culture?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 13850, "name": "Malay World", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malay_World?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 20109, "name": "Religion and Modernity", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Religion_and_Modernity?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 28878, "name": "Television Drama", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television_Drama?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 72282, "name": "Television Consumption", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television_Consumption?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 511009, "name": "Consumption Culture", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Consumption_Culture?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 702728, "name": "Watching Competencies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Watching_Competencies?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 723155, "name": "Malay Women", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malay_Women?f_ri=72282"}, {"id": 977410, "name": "Malaysian Modernity", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malaysian_Modernity?f_ri=72282"}]}, {"id": 36849078, "title": "Television overconsumption and underconsumption in Spain", "created_at": "2018-06-15T06:37:30.604-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/36849078/Television_overconsumption_and_underconsumption_in_Spain?f_ri=72282", "dom_id": "work_36849078", "summary": "Television viewing is one of the activities to which we devote a significant amount of time every day. At times, however, people may watch less TV than they would like (underconsumption), while at other times, the opposite is the case (overconsumption). In this context, the aim of this study was to analyze the sociodemographic characteristics of viewers and explore television behaviors associated with a greater incidence of television overconsumption and underconsumption. The statistical information is drawn from a sample of 1,000 Spanish viewers. Our results indicate that both overconsumption and underconsumption are more prevalent among women than among men, and that viewers between 65 and 74 years old are those whose television consumption best matches their personal wishes. Overconsumption is more closely linked with watching several TV programs at the same time, and continuing to watch television even though the content does not appeal to the viewer. Underconsumption is related to switching on the TV set without knowing what is on. The results obtained show the need to take into account quantity, not only quality, in studies of television viewing. They also show that television underconsumption and overconsumption are complex phenomena that require inquiry from a multidisciplinary range of analytical perspectives.", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 56801574, "asset_id": 36849078, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 82640400, "first_name": "Revista", "last_name": "An\u00e0lisi", "domain_name": "uab", "page_name": "RevistaAnalisi", "display_name": "Revista  An\u00e0lisi", "profile_url": "https://uab.academia.edu/RevistaAnalisi?f_ri=72282", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/82640400/19892187/19703829/s65_revista.an_lisi.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 1571, "name": "Television Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television_Studies?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 54718, "name": "Media Consumption", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Media_Consumption?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 54734, "name": "Media Research", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Media_Research?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 72282, "name": "Television Consumption", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television_Consumption?f_ri=72282", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 2974297, "name": "Television-viewing habits", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Television-viewing_habits?f_ri=72282"}]}, {"id": 13052348, "title": "Pantallas para ver el mundo. Estereotipaci\u00f3n televisiva de la poblaci\u00f3n ind\u00edgena mexicana y generaci\u00f3n de prejuicio", "created_at": "2015-06-17T08:22:40.663-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/13052348/Pantallas_para_ver_el_mundo_Estereotipaci%C3%B3n_televisiva_de_la_poblaci%C3%B3n_ind%C3%ADgena_mexicana_y_generaci%C3%B3n_de_prejuicio?f_ri=72282", "dom_id": "work_13052348", "summary": null, "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 45736426, "asset_id": 13052348, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 32704233, "first_name": "Alma Rosa Saldierna", "last_name": "Salas", "domain_name": "uanl", "page_name": "AlmaRosaSaldiernaSalas", "display_name": "Alma Rosa Saldierna Salas", "profile_url": "https://uanl.academia.edu/AlmaRosaSaldiernaSalas?f_ri=72282", "photo": "/images/s65_no_pic.png"}, {"id": 32287636, "first_name": "Felipe", "last_name": "Mara\u00f1\u00f3n", "domain_name": "uanl", "page_name": "FelipeMara\u00f1\u00f3n", "display_name": "Felipe Mara\u00f1\u00f3n", "profile_url": "https://uanl.academia.edu/FelipeMara%C3%B1%C3%B3n?f_ri=72282", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/32287636/17174006/17317025/s65_felipe.mara_n.jpg"}, {"id": 8991389, "first_name": "Adriana Rodriguez", "last_name": "Rodriguez", "domain_name": "independent", "page_name": "AdrianaRodriguezRodriguez", "display_name"